ic, Between Camp and Cursi considers how this body of twentieth- and twenty-first-century literature has challenged heteronormativity in Mexico and wrestled more broadly with both the colonial underpinnings of modernity and hegemonic Western gender norms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aGender identityzMexico. 0aHomosexuality in literature. 0aHumor in literature. 0aMexican literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aQueer theory. 4aGender and Sexuality : Gender Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Lesbian / Gay Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Queer Studies. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Latin American Studies. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2022z978311149185140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848667340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438486673423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438486673/original  a978-3-11-149185-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles